The Great Oasis (Deepwell Confluence) is the primary water source in the eastern desert — three underground springs rising through fractured limestone into a shallow basin ringed by date palms. It is the only reliable year-round water source within six days' travel in any direction; all desert caravan routes converge here because the oasis did not sit on the road but the road existed because the oasis did. The Keepers of Measure built three infrastructure types: the Cistern Ring (underground catchment chambers regulating flow, template for all subsequent desert cisterns), the Waystone Circle (twelve upright slabs with directional glyphs and the Charter of Passage asserting every proper-route traveler's right to draw water), and the Measuring House (observatory, archive, and administrative headquarters centered on the gnomon stone). The High Water Court evolved from the original four-member cistern sluice council into a hereditary judicial bureaucracy managing the entire eastern road network's water-right disputes. After the Ninth Meridian Rite failed and drought intensified, the underground springs diminished. The Battle of the Dry Basin — fought between pragmatist militia, legalist charter guards, and ritualist shrine warriors — destroyed the Toll Pavilion, collapsed two cistern chambers, and killed the last High Water Judge. Three successor factions now control different parts of the oasis: Spring Wardens (pragmatist descendants controlling surviving springs and the north cistern, the closest thing to legitimate authority), Jackal Synod Oasis Chapter (ritualist faction occupying Toll Pavilion ruins, following Wellmouth Creed doctrine), and Dune Reavers (former charter militia descendants controlling approach roads and taxing arrivals).

