Khephari geological analysis of the Great Oasis identifies the underground spring system as a fracture-limestone aquifer dependent on distant recharge zones that the Iseth Reach river once fed directly. The river's drying severed the recharge connection; the springs did not immediately fail because the aquifer had stored water under pressure, but the long-term drawdown was inevitable once recharge stopped. The Ninth Meridian Rite's failure did not cause the springs to diminish — it accelerated a process already underway. The cistern ring was correctly engineered for flood regulation, not drought survival, because the original Keeper-period engineers were building for a world where the Iseth Reach still functioned. The design was appropriate to conditions; the conditions changed. The third spring's failure approximately fifty years ago is consistent with a continued aquifer pressure reduction at the rate that the hydrology implies; the remaining two springs have a calculable remaining useful lifespan under current draw rates that the Spring Wardens have not formally assessed.
